      {
        "paragraph_index": 4,
        "text": "### 🧪 Chemistry Context\n\nFrom the broader literature (outside SRD-46), uranyl (UO₂²⁺) does form complexes with crown ethers, particularly in non-aqueous or mixed-solvent media. For example:\n- **18-Crown-6** has been reported to weakly complex UO₂²⁺ in organic solvents (e.g., acetonitrile, propylene carbonate), with log β₁ values typically in the range of **1–3**, but aqueous stability constants are very limited due to competition from hydration and hydrolysis.\n- Crown ethers are more commonly used with uranyl in **solvent extraction** contexts rather than aqueous equilibrium studies.\n\nFor quantitative stability constant data on uranyl–crown ether systems, I recommend consulting:\n- **IUPAC SC-Database** or **NIST SRD-46 supplementary literature** directly\n- Specific papers on uranyl extraction chemistry (e.g., work by Moyer, Lumetta, or Sessler on macrocyclic uranyl complexation)\n\n*Source: NIST SRD-46 database (queried via API); no uranium entries were found.*",
